Point Process in INLA

Im going to try and run a point process on the VPS data in INLA, heavily following the method outlined in (Moraga 2020). The same author also has a free geospatial statistics with INLA textbook (Moraga 2019). Id like an excuse to learn INLA, as it is supposed to be a Bayesian method that runs much more quickly than Monte Carlo-based methods, like JAGS or Stan. Ive tried to use the brms package before, and tend to like it because it uses the same syntax as mgcv and lme4, for instance, but it takes a while to run all of the simulations on my computer.

The following is just pulling in all of the data.

Spatial gymnastics

Here is where we stand with all the data we just imported:

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mh_shape) +
  geom_sf(data = habitat, aes(fill = Group)) +
  geom_sf(data = fish, alpha = 0.03, color = 'red') +
  theme_minimal()

The code above imported any polygon that overlapped with the cropped Marshyhope Creek section. Now we want the full intersection basically, we want to have it cropped down another level.

habitat <- habitat %>% 
  st_intersection(mh_shape)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all
## geometries
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mh_shape) +
  geom_sf(data = habitat, aes(fill = Group)) +

We can now see that there are areas that were not classified by the NOAA survey (even as Unclassified). They are the surrounding bits that are in gray. We now want to pull those bits out and classify them as Unclassified

# Select the important bits
habitat <- habitat %>% 
  select(Group)

# Union the habitat polygons (lump them into one big polygon) and then subtract
#   that from the Marshyhope polygon
uncl <- st_sym_difference(st_union(habitat), mh_shape)

plot(uncl, col = 'blue')

# Add the new unclassified back in
habitat <- uncl %>% 
  st_as_sf()  %>% 
  rename(Shape = x) %>% 
  mutate(Group = 'Unclassified') %>% 
  rbind(habitat)

habitat
# Since we don't actually need each individual polygon indexed, we'll group
#   them all together
habitat <- habitat %>% 
  group_by(Group) %>% 
  summarize(geometry = st_union(Shape))

habitat
ggplot(data = habitat) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Group))

Adapting the data to fit

(Moraga 2020) creates a raster::raster data set to discretize the point data, which they then convert back to a vector. I think that I can just discretize the data in sf, cutting out the raster middle-man. Note that INLA will eventually want grid indexes to run top to bottom, then left to right.

Make the grid

grid_full <- habitat %>%
  # Our coordinate reference system has units of meters
  #   Make a 20m x 20m grid
  st_make_grid(c(20, 20)) %>% 
  
  # Create IDs in the INLA order (top to bottom then left to right)
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  mutate(centroid = st_centroid(x)) %>% 
  cbind(st_coordinates(.$centroid)) %>% 
  arrange(X, desc(Y)) %>% 
  transmute(id = rownames(.))

# Select those grid cells that are covered by the polgyon or overlap with the
#   outline of Marshyhope Creek
grid <- grid_full[st_covered_by(grid_full, mh_shape, sparse = F) |
                    st_overlaps(grid_full, mh_shape, sparse = F),]

plot(st_geometry(grid_full))
plot(st_geometry(grid), add = T, col = 'red')
plot(st_geometry(habitat), add = T)

Descritize habitat covariate (winner takes all)

Each grid cell will be assigned the bottom type that covers the most area in that grid cell.

bot_type <- grid %>%
  
  # Crop the habitat polygons by each grid cell
  st_intersection(habitat) %>% 
  
  # Calculate the area of each bottom type in the grid cell
  mutate(area = st_area(x)) %>% 
  
  # Select the greatest area in each grid cell
  group_by(id) %>% 
  filter(area == max(area)) %>% 
  data.frame()
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all
## geometries
# Join the above back in with the grid
grid <- grid %>% 
  left_join(bot_type[, names(bot_type) %in% c('id', 'Group')])
## Joining, by = "id"
ggplot(data = grid) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Group)) +
  geom_sf(data = habitat, fill = NA, color = 'white') + 
  theme_minimal()

Match fish detections with winner take all habitat grid

Now we find into which winner-take-all habitat each position fell and add that up for each grid cell and transmitter.

fish_grid_id <- fish %>% 
  st_transform(st_crs(grid)) %>% 
  st_intersection(grid) %>% 
  group_by(id, transmitter) %>% 
  summarize(n_pos = n()) 
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all
## geometries
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'id'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
n_pos_grid <- grid %>% 
  full_join(select(data.frame(fish_grid_id), id, transmitter, n_pos)) %>% 
  mutate(n_pos = ifelse(is.na(n_pos), 0, n_pos))
## Joining, by = "id"
ggplot(data = n_pos_grid) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = Group, alpha = n_pos), color = NA) +
  facet_wrap(~ transmitter) +
  theme_minimal()

Get data ready for INLA

mod_data <- n_pos_grid %>% 
  mutate(
    # Numeric ID for spatial random effects
    id = as.numeric(id),
    # Factor transmitter for iid random effects
    transmitter = as.factor(transmitter),
    
    # Area for offset
    area = as.numeric(st_area(x)),
    # Factorize group since that helps sometimes
    Group = as.factor(Group)
    )

Run the model

library(INLA)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loading required package: parallel
## Loading required package: sp
## This is INLA_21.02.23 built 2021-02-22 21:11:05 UTC.
##  - See www.r-inla.org/contact-us for how to get help.
##  - Save 379.7Mb of storage running 'inla.prune()'
res <- inla(n_pos ~ 1 + Group +
              
              # Random transmitter effect
              f(transmitter, model = 'iid') +
              
              # Random walk random effect -- "rw2d" for use on a grid
              f(id, model = 'rw2d',
                # Needs the number of rows and columns
                #   Using the bounding box divided by grid size
                ncol = (st_bbox(grid)$xmax - st_bbox(grid)$xmin) / 20,
                nrow = (st_bbox(grid)$ymax - st_bbox(grid)$ymin) / 20),
            family = "poisson", data = mod_data,
            E = area,
            control.predictor = list(compute = TRUE),
            control.compute = list(waic = TRUE))

Results

Fixed effects

First, well look at the posterior of the bottom type fixed effect.

list_marginals_fixed <- res$marginals.fixed

marginals <- data.frame(do.call(rbind, list_marginals_fixed))
marginals$group <- rep(names(list_marginals_fixed),
                       times = sapply(list_marginals_fixed, nrow))


ggplot(data = marginals,
       aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +
  labs(x = expression(beta[1]), y = "Density") +
  facet_wrap(~ group, scales = 'free') +
  theme_minimal()

The Intercept in the plot of the marginals is mud: the coefficient for mud is significantly less than zero. All of the other bottom types are no different than zero (i.e.: they arent significant).

summary_fixed <- res$summary.fixed %>% 
  mutate(group = gsub('Group', '', row.names(.)),
         group = ifelse(group == '(Intercept)', 'Mud', group),
         group = factor(group, levels = c('Sandy_Gravel', 'Sand', 'Muddy_Sand',
                                          'Sandy_Clay', 'Sandy_Mud', 'Mud',
                                          'Unclassified'),
                        ordered = T))

ggplot(data = summary_fixed) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(x = group, y = `0.5quant`,
                      ymin = `0.025quant`, ymax = `0.975quant`)) +
  labs(x = 'Bottom type', y = 'Effect') +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(data = filter(summary_fixed, group != 'Mud')) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(x = group, y = `0.5quant`,
                      ymin = `0.025quant`, ymax = `0.975quant`)) +
  labs(x = 'Bottom type', y = 'Effect') +
  theme_minimal()

If we look at the median and confidence interval of the coefficients on the same scale we can see that the effect of mud is very poorly resolved. In fact, we need to remove it to see whats going on with the other bottom types. As we saw before, none of the other bottom types are significantly different than zero. Sandy mud is almost there, but still no luck.

What does this look like on the response scale (number of positions per 20 m x 20 m grid)?

summary_fixed <- summary_fixed %>% 
  mutate(resp_0.025quant = exp(`0.025quant`),
         resp_0.5quant = exp(`0.5quant`),
         resp_0.975quant = exp(`0.975quant`))

ggplot(data = summary_fixed) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(x = group, y = resp_0.5quant,
                      ymin = resp_0.025quant, ymax = resp_0.975quant)) +
  labs(x = 'Bottom type', y = 'Effect') +
  theme_minimal()

Here, we can see again that mud is predicted to have basically no positions and all other bottom types are roughly equivalent around one position. All in all, bottom type can account for 0-2 positions in each grid cell.

Random effects

First is the random effect of transmitter (individual fish). There do seem to be some differences here, though no individual fish is significantly different from the others. Note that since this is included as a random effect, everything is pulled toward the mean this is likely to underestimate large differences. Might be interesting to see if there are any female fish in here.

summary_iid <- res$summary.random$transmitter

ggplot(data = summary_iid) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(x = ID, y = `0.5quant`,
                      ymin = `0.025quant`, ymax = `0.975quant`)) +
  labs(x = 'Transmitter', y = 'Effect') +
  theme_minimal()

Next is the interesting part: spatial autocorrelation! It looks like there are some hot spots not explained by sediment type or transmitter just north of the Brookview Bridge and near the southern end of the array. Note the scale of the effect up to 7 more positions per fish in each grid cell! That far outweighs the 0-2 due to bottom type and is on the same order as the 1-6 due to differences between fish.

mod_data <- mod_data %>% 
  mutate(re_spat = res$summary.random$id[mod_data$id, "0.5quant"])

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = distinct(mod_data, id, .keep_all = T),
          aes(fill = re_spat), color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = mh_shape, fill = NA, size = 1, color = 'black') +
  labs(fill = 'Effect') +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  theme_minimal()

To me, this really looks like what I imagine the depth to look like in the area. Two things are neat to me with this:

  1. Weve accidentally used Atlantic sturgeon to create an index of depth in Marshyhope Creek!
  2. It displays in a nice, visual manner that a depth covariate would be very informative.
  3. We now know that bottom type really isnt very predictive of the number of detections in a grid cell.

Predictions

Lastly, well run some predictions.

cellarea <- 20*20
mod_data$pred <- res$summary.fitted.values[, "0.5quant"] * cellarea
mod_data$lci <- res$summary.fitted.values[, "0.025quant"] * cellarea
mod_data$uci <- res$summary.fitted.values[, "0.975quant"] * cellarea

preds <- mod_data %>% 
  group_by(id) %>% 
  summarise(s_pred = sum(pred),
            s_lci = sum(lci),
            s_uci = sum(uci))


library(patchwork) 
pred_plot <- ggplot(data = preds) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = s_pred), color = NA, show.legend = F) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(limits = c(0, 150)) +
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(plot.margin = margin(0, 0, 0, 0))
  
lci_plot <- ggplot(data = preds) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = s_lci), color = NA) +
  labs(fill = 'Prediction', subtitle = 'LCI') +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(limits = c(0, 150)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text = element_blank(),
        plot.margin = margin(0, 0, 0, 0))
  
uci_plot <- ggplot(data = preds) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = s_uci), color = NA) +
  labs(fill = 'Prediction', subtitle = 'UCI') +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(limits = c(0, 150)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text = element_blank(),
        plot.margin = margin(0, 0, 0, 0))

pred_plot + (lci_plot / uci_plot) + plot_layout(widths = c(2.2,1), guides = 'collect')

In a spatial point process model utilizing a fixed effect of bottom type and random effects of space and transmitter, following the algorithm outlined in Moraga (2020), we have predicted the combined number of positions of various fish within a 20m x 20m grid in this area of Marshyhope Creek. Total predicted positions in each grid cell ranged from 0 - 117 (CIs: 0 - 0; 10 - 141) with a median of 3 (CI: 1 - 5). The highest number of positions seem to be in the middle of the creek, with concentrations located above Brookview Bridge and at the southernmost bend in our array.

Mud had significantly fewer positions than all other bottom types. Other bottom types did not vary significantly from each other, nor were they significant in the model.

The spatial random effect, which represents unknown spatially-autocorrelated variables, could create a difference of more than 7 positions per fish in a given 20m x 20m cell. As the highest intensity mirrors the channel of the Marshyhope, this is likely to be due to association with depth. Differences associated with individual fish also cause differences of 1-6 positions per cell.

Compared to the random effects of spatial autocorrelation and individual fish, which were on the order of 0-7 detections, the fixed effect of bottom type, which ranged from 0-2 positions, was not as great. As is clear from the spatial random effect, bottom type is not a dominant nor even informative predictor of Atlantic sturgeon positions in the VPS. A crucial next step for informative modeling of Atlantic sturgeon detections would be to collect bathymetry data in this area of the Marshyhope in at least a 20 x 20m scale.
